“However, we don’t see the same move from the U.S. side,” he said.
“If we can’t trust the U.S. side, then we won’t be able to confidently secure our national security, and in such a situation, there’s no way we can unilaterally disarm ourselves first.”
While Ri repeated North Korea’s familiar complaint that Washington refused to denuclearize “stage by stage” and that North Korea would receive the corresponding benefit of taking steps, his remarks have a notable point of not rejecting unilateral nuclear disarmament as Pyongyang had previously refused.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, in which he pledged to work towards “denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula,” while Trump promised to ensure North Korea’s security.
North Korea is still trying to find a way to formally end the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States insists that Pyongyang must give up its nuclear weapons first.
Washington is also opposed to calls for an easing of harsh international sanctions against North Korea.
“The United States insists on ‘first nuclear disarmament’ and increases the pressure by sanctions to achieve its goals in a coercive manner, even protesting the ‘declaration of an end to war’,” Ri said.
“The notion that sanctions can make us fall on our knees is just a wild dream for those who don’t understand us.
But the problem here is that the sanctions that remain in place continue to lose our trust.”
Ri made no mention of plans to hold a second summit between Kim and Trump, as the U.S. leader presented at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the foreign minister referred to three meetings between Kim and South Korean President Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the negotiating party on the issue of nuclear disarmament is South Korea, not the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula will not fall into the current deadlock.”
Ri’s tone, however, was different from last year’s, when he told the General Assembly that North Korea’s launch of missiles on the U.S. mainland was inevitable on a suicide mission after Trump called Kim “the Rocket Man.”
Last year at the United Nations, Trump threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, but this year praised Kim for taking bold steps to disarm, but Trump also stressed that much more needs to be done and sanctions must remain in place until North Korea denuclearizes.
On Wednesday, Trump said he didn’t set a deadline for this: “Two years, three years or just five months doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia say the U.N. Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its efforts.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday: “The Security Council sanctions must continue to be vigorously and uncompromisingly enforced until we can confirm the results of complete, final denuclearization with verifiable evidence.”
The Security Council has agreed to step up sanctions against North Korea since 2006 to block funding for Pyongyang’s nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo held talks with Ri on the sidelines of official U.N. General Assembly meetings and said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
