Harvard students take a course on full rest
In an effort to combat the machine-pressure learning culture, with 'night owl students' drinking coffee instead of water, a new course at Harvard University this year has encouraged all college students to sleep more.
Students studying at the world’s number one university often don’t know the basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School, and an expert at Women’s Hospital, and Brigham, who designed the course, believes it to be the first of its kind in the United States.
The inspiration for starting this course came after he attended a talk about the impact of sleep deprivation on the learning process.
“After the end of the talk, a female student came up to me and said, ‘Why did you know this in the last year?’
She said no one told her about the importance of sleep, which really surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, introduced for the first time this year, explains to students how the importance of good sleep habits enhances academic and athletic performance, while improving their overall health.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and the university’s chief executive of health services, said the school decided to introduce the course after finding students with severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course covers a wide range of interactive tasks.
In a section featuring a dormitory room image, students can click on coffee mugs, curtains, workout machines and books to learn about how caffeine, light and sleep deprivation affect their performance, as well as the importance of forming a bedtime routine on time.
In another section, participants were asked how long-term sleep deprivation could increase their risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
Then, the university campus map, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
“We know that this course cannot immediately change students’ behavior.
But we believe they have a right to know – just as you have a right to know the health impact of choosing to smoke,” Czeisler added.
He said that the culture that prides itself on “night owl students” still exists, while modern technologies and growing pressure on students to lead to sleep deprivation is an increasingly serious problem.
Ensuring adequate sleep, good sleep quality should become a student’s ‘secret weapon’ to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety – even to avoid weight gain, because lack of sleep causes the brain to fall into a state of hunger, leading us to constantly starve.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student in California who was studying biology, chemistry and physics, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, and he also took one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course helped him ‘open his eyes’ and inspired him to make an effort to organize a course within the whole school.
He hopes that the next step will be to ask all postgraduates to take a similar program of study before starting to compete in the main course.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students take into consideration when setting bedtime, waking hours, and being aware of the harmful effects of the ‘blue light’ emitted by electronic displays and LEDs, which can cause circadian arrhythmia, resulting in difficulty sleeping.
