Update on Red tide phenomenon: Decreased red tide density in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Association shows that the density of the red tide has decreased in much of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, algal blooms have been reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties – this causes the red tide density to decrease.
The phenomenon of the Red tide spread for about 130 miles along the northern coast of Pinellas to the south of Lee County.
Small patches were also found within 10 miles off Hillsborough County, but fewer locations than last week.
Red tides have also been observed in Pasco County.
Average densities along the coast or offshore Pinellas County have been reported over the past week, low to high densities off the coast of Hillsborough County, low to high densities in Manatee County, low to high densities off the coast of Sarasota County, low to high densities off Charlotte County, low to high densities along the coast or offshore at Lee County, and low densities at Collier County.
Respiratory irritation continues to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
Respiratory irritation has not been reported in northwestern Florida over the past week.
